            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.2"/>
                
                <note>ans. 6/13/72</note>
                
                <note>x</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">2</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">COMMERCE BANK
                        <lb/>
                    922 WALNUT STREET 
                        <lb/>
                    KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI</hi> 64141
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>June 5, 1972</dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Doctor Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It has been twelve years since I was first introduced to your writings in your Epic of America course at the University of Missouri. Since that time I have retained and often re-read excerpts form your Cycle of the West, and have recently begun to introduce my seven year old son to the book. I hope that he will be instructed and continually reminded, as I have been, by your books about what it means to be a man in a world of changing values and more rapidly changing yardsticks for measuring men.</p> 
                
                <p>I was again recently touched by your message upon reading Black Elk Speaks and was pleasantly surprised to find that my son could also understand and enjoy excerpts from the book. The book was perhaps even more enjoyable as I read it in conjunction with Bury My Heart at Wounded Knee and a re-reading of your Song of the Mesiah and the Song of Hugh Glass. I only hope that the University will continue to offer course work based on your writings, although they could certainly never replace the manner in which you presented the work. I can think of no better way to insure that we, as a people, can be reminded that we two-leggeds must share life with the four-leggeds and the wings of the air and all green things, as children of one mother and our Father, the one Spirit.</p> 
                
                <p>Thank you for the Cycle of the West, Black Elk, and, most of all, your presentation of the material in your class. I would hope that some day in the near future on one of my visits to Columbia, I could have the opportunity to visit with you personally again.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Best regards,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Bill Haw</signed> 
                    <signed>C. L. William Haw 
                    Senior Vice President</signed>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>c/o University of Missouri</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Department of American Literature</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
